(74, 41, 'Cellular Telephones Vocab', 'Jonathan Almawi', '2016-05-05', 'ph1.jpg', '<p><strong>Cellular Telephones &ndash; Pages 90 &ndash; 93 </strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>1) What is the type of signal cellular telephones use:</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">VLF (very low frequency) 3-30kHz</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>2) Explain why two channels are required for users to carry on a conversation:</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">One will transmit the data to the user that requires to use it, and from there the user will transmit their data to show what they need in return to give back.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>3) Explain the solution the FCC came up with in regards to dividing the country into MSAs:</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Each market, which usually economically passes an entire metropolitan area.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>4) Approximately how big of an area does a &ldquo;cell&rdquo; cover:</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">50 miles in radius</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>5) Explain why the cellular telephone is in fact called the cellular telephone:</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It lets the user call over the &ldquo;radio&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>6) What is a CTSO:</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cellular telephone switching office</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>7) Explain why a cell phone retransmits its ID Information so frequently:</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So its able to get a network to connect/ transmit data. It has to transmit its ID a lot to ensure the information is correct for the user.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>8) Describe a problem that may occur if a cell phone does not do what is suggested in question 7.</strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If the phone connects to a network that prohibits some actions then when a user tries to do that action it will be blocked.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'cellular tech, phones, telephones, signal, channels, channel, FCC, VLF, CTSO', '', 'published', 4),
(75, 1, 'Review Questions on page 135...', 'Johnny', '2016-05-05', 'Fibre-Channel.jpg', '<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Jonathan Almawi</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Review Questions on page 135. Questions 2,7,8,9,12,14,15</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n<li><strong>What are the four components of an interface? </strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">electrical component, mechanical component, functional component and procedural component</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol start="7">\r\n<li><strong>What is the difference between SCSI and iSCSI?</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;"> ISCSI is a protocol that helps remote access of data over the internet. It can be called the link between two data hubs in varied locations. Internet SCSI is business oriented. A storage area network (SAN) is created using TCP/IP technology to communicate between two separate devices. There is no need for traditional cable system to connect to a network. This is facilitated only by Internet SCSI SAN.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Internet SCSI technology has helped a great deal of people access their files sitting at any corner of the world. Traditional FTP protocol needs a person to transfer a file from a home computer to an office computer but ISCSI has broken all the barriers and can help transfer information without the assistance of anyone. An individual can directly log onto the Internet SCSI hard drive irrespective of wherever he/she is. The greatest advantage of Internet SCSI is that data can be sent in both directions. The protocol is bilateral. </span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol start="8">\r\n<li><strong>Are InfiniBand and Fibre Channel likely to be used on your home computer? </strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">No, they are deemed for high volume/speed data environments mostly, supercomputer clusters etc.</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol start="9">\r\n<li><strong>In asynchronous connections, what additional bits are added to a character to prepare it for transfer? </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To prepare a data character for transmission, a few extra bits of information, a few extra bits of information of the character to create a small packet of a bit.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol start="12">\r\n<li><strong> What are the advantages and disadvantages of asynchronous communication?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Advantage:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> The character is self contained &amp; Transmitter and receiver need not be synchronized</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Transmitting and receiving clocks are independent of each other</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Disadvantage:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Overhead of start and stop bits</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> False recognition of these bits due to noise on the channel</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><br /></p>\r\n<ol start="14">\r\n<li><strong> What are the advantages and disadvantages of synchronous communication?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Advantage:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> This reduces overhead bits</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> It overcomes the two main deficiencies of the asynchronous method, that of inefficiency and lack of error detection.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Disadvantage:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> For correct operation the receiver must start to sample the line at the correct instant</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol start="15">\r\n<li><strong> What is the difference between a point-to-point connection and a multipoint connection?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Point-to-multipoint allows you to connect up to eight separate devices to the box on the wall.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Point-to-point allows you to connect just one device. This is usually a PBX.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Fibre channel, infiniband, home computer, SCSI, iSCSI, Review Questions', '', 'published', 0),
